><section class="core-article-notes"><h4>Notes</h4><div role="paragraph">Knowledge of the finer anatomic details of the atria, ventricles, cardiac valves, pericardial recesses, and paracardiac structures and their radiologic appearances will help prevent misinterpretation of normal anatomic structures as pathologic processes.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-authors"><h4>Affiliations</h4><div id="con1" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Lynn S.</span> <span property="familyName">Broderick</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Department of Radiology, University of Wisconsin-Madison Medical School, E3/311 Clinical Science Center, 600 Highland Ave, Madison, WI 53792. Presented as an education exhibit at the 2003 RSNA Scientific Assembly. Received April 14, 2004; revision requested June 8 and received August 3; accepted August 5. All authors have no financial relationships to disclose.</span></div></div><div class="core-author-link"><a href="/authored-by/Broderick/Lynn+S" rel="nofollow">View all articles by this author</a></div></div></div><div id="con2" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Gregory N.</span> <span property="familyName">Brooks</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Department of Radiology, University of Wisconsin-Madison Medical School, E3/311 Clinical Science Center, 600 Highland Ave, Madison, WI 53792. Presented as an education exhibit at the 2003 RSNA Scientific Assembly. Received April 14, 2004; revision requested June 8 and received August 3; accepted August 5. All authors have no financial re